        "id": 5120
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-09T16:34:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m wondering if rather than configuring key-value data on the local machine, we should just proxy metadata requests to a \"skolo\" GCE project. E.g. if this server gets a request for \"/computeMetadata/v1/project/attributes/{key}\", it would in turn query \"https://www.googleapis.com/compute/v1/projects/skolo/attributes/{key}\".\n\nThis wouldn\u0027t work for instance metadata, unless we want to map that to specially-formatted project-level metadata.\n\nAnother option would be to store key-value data in GCS (with caching).",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 154,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 155,
        "endChar": 73
      },
      "revId": "4e863933c9def34172ade3e044b51836e2c5de26",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1c6be6cf_42fcd4b1",
        "filename": "go/metadata/server.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 155,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-09T18:21:53Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "What do you think about Joe\u0027s idea to check metadata into a private Git repo?  I think we\u0027re really just talking about project-level metadata here, so maybe there\u0027s no need to bother with instance-level metadata.  I was imagining that some process running in GCE would sync the metadata repo and push the values into actual GCE metadata on a periodic basis.  Metadata on the jumphosts would work similarly: the metadata file just gets pushed to the machine, and this server would periodically read the file.",
      "parentUuid": "2c9127cd_ddaeb543",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 154,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 155,
        "endChar": 73
      },
      "revId": "4e863933c9def34172ade3e044b51836e2c5de26",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
